ted Kingdom"},"nl":{"1219–1262":"1219–1262","1223–1261":"1223–1261","1225–1240":"1225–1240","1227–1261":"1227–1261","1225–1273":"1225–1273","1243–1303":"1243–1303","1193–1238":"1193–1238","1197–1263":"1197–1263","1263":"1263","1197":"1197","1262":"1262","1273":"1273","1240":"1240","1261":"1261","1193":"1193","1238":"1238","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1303":"1303","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1223":"1223","about 1238":"circa 1238","1243":"1243","24 December 1243":"24 december 1243","1219":"1219","1218":"1218","Mitford, Northumberland, England":"Mitford, Northumberland, England","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","Bothal, Northumberland, Eng":"Bothal, Northumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1219–1262":"1219–1262","1223–1261":"1223–1261","1225–1240":"1225–1240","1227–1261":"1227–1261","1225–1273":"1225–1273","1243–1303":"1243–1303","1193–1238":"1193–1238","1197–1263":"1197–1263","1263":"1263","1197":"1197","1262":"1262","1273":"1273","1240":"1240","1261":"1261","1193":"1193","1238":"1238","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1303":"1303","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1223":"1223","about 1238":"about 1238","1243":"1243","24 December 1243":"24 December 1243","1219":"1219","1218":"1218","Mitford, Northumberland, England":"Mitford, Northumberland, England","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","Bothal, Northumberland, Eng":"Bothal, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bertram","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German, English (mainly in southeastern Scotland, of Norman origin), French, and Danish: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Bertram</i>, composed of the elements <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ + <i>hramn</i> ‘raven’. The raven was the bird of Odin, king of the gods, in ancient Germanic mythology. The personal name was common in France throughout the Middle Ages (especially in the form   Bertrand  ), where its popularity was increased by the fame of the troubadour Bertrand de Born (<i>c.</i> 1140–1214). The name was taken to England by the Normans in the forms <i>Bertran(d)</i>, <i>Bertram</i>, and <i>Bartram</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Beltrami","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Dante, Dino, Marco, Pio, Sal, Tullio.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the personal name <i>Beltrame</i>, from an ancient Germanic name composed of the elements <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ + <i>hramn</i> ‘raven’. See also   Bertram  ."]},{"name":"Bartram","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and North German: variant of   Bertram  .","History: William Bartram, a Quaker, had a large farm near Darby, PA, when his eldest son, John, the first American botanist, was born in 1699. John conducted botanical experiments at his own farm in Kingsessing, PA, near Philadelphia."]},{"name":"Bertman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Frieda, Wilhelm.","Americanized form of German <b>Bertmann</b>: altered form (by folk etymology) of   Bertram  ."]},{"name":"Bethke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Eldor, Ewald, Otto, Rudi, Wilhelmina.","North German: from a pet form of the ancient Germanic personal names   Bertram   or   Berthold  . See also   Beth  ."]},{"name":"Bertrand","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Armand, Monique, Francois, Gilles, Raoul, Emile, Herve, Jacques, Jean-Marie, Odette.","French, Walloon, and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from the French personal name <i>Bertrand</i>, a variant of   Bertram  , coined by folk etymology under the influence of the present participle endings <i>-and</i>, <i>-ant</i>.","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."]},{"name":"Beltran","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Manuel, Carlos, Jesus, Luis, Pedro, Jorge, Mario, Ricardo, Francisco, Rafael.","Spanish (<b>Beltrán</b>), Catalan, and southern French: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ + <i>hramn</i> ‘raven’. See also   Bertram  ."]},{"name":"Beltramo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo.","Italian: from the medieval personal name <i>Beltramo</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see   Bertram  )."]},{"name":"Bert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Philibert, Pierre.","German, French, and Polish: from a short form of various compound personal names formed with ancient Germanic <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ (see for example   Bertram  ).","English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Berte</i> (Old French <i>Berte</i>, from ancient Germanic   Berta  )."]},{"name":"Battermann","meanings":["German:","possibly an occupational name for a merchant or peddler, from <i>Bartermann</i>.","alternatively, perhaps from a short form of the personal name   Bertram   + Middle High German <i>man</i> ‘man’."]},{"name":"Bertran","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Jorge, Eduardo, Enrique, Joaquin, Ricardo, Aleida, Ana, Ana Maria, Elena, Felipe, Jeronimo.  French Andre.","French, Occitan, and Catalan: variant of   Bertram   or   Bertrand  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":5,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":40,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger Bertram Baron of Bothal was born in 1219, in Northumberland, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard Bertram Baron of Bothal, was 26 and his mother, Mrs Sarah Bertram, was 22. He had at least 1 son with Isabel de Ros. He died in 1262, in Northumberland, England, at the age of 43, and was buried in Mitford, Northumberland, England."},"et":{"1219–1262":"1219–1262","1223–1261":"1223–1261","1225–1240":"1225–1240","1227–1261":"1227–1261","1225–1273":"1225–1273","1243–1303":"1243–1303","1193–1238":"1193–1238","1197–1263":"1197–1263","1263":"1263","1197":"1197","1262":"1262","1273":"1273","1240":"1240","1261":"1261","1193":"1193","1238":"1238","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1303":"1303","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1223":"1223","about 1238":"umbes 1238","1243":"1243","24 December 1243":"24. detsember 1243","1219":"1219","1218":"1218","Mitford, Northumberland, England":"Mitford, Northumberland, England","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","Bothal, Northumberland, Eng":"Bothal, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1219–1262":"1219–126